, Cheshire, England":"Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"1085–from 1142 to 1182":"1085–van 1142 to 1182","1080–1135":"1080–1135","1105–1140":"1105–1140","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1136–1244":"1136–1244","1085–1182":"1085–1182","1080":"1080","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1105":"1105","from 1142 to 1182":"van 1142 to 1182","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","about 1105":"circa 1105","1244":"1244","about 1135":"circa 1135","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England","Kingsley, Cheshire, England":"Kingsley, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1085–from 1142 to 1182":"1085–from 1142 to 1182","1080–1135":"1080–1135","1105–1140":"1105–1140","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1136–1244":"1136–1244","1085–1182":"1085–1182","1080":"1080","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1105":"1105","from 1142 to 1182":"from 1142 to 1182","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","about 1105":"about 1105","1244":"1244","about 1135":"about 1135","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England","Kingsley, Cheshire, England":"Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Moston (Lancs), Moston by Chester or Moston Green (both Cheshire), or Moston in Stanton upon Hine Heath (Shrops). There has probably been some confusion with (2).","2  Welsh, English:  see  Mostyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mosson","meanings":["1  English: in Gloucs perhaps a variant of   Mawson  . Compare Tacie Mawson, 1570 in   IGI   (Elmore, Gloucs); John Mawson, 1645 in   IGI   (Kings Stanley, Gloucs). Otherwise see (2).","2  English: variant of   Moston   with assimilation of the /t/ to the preceding /s/. Compare Jois. Mosson, 1620, Thomæ Moston, 1630 in   IGI   (Astbury, Cheshire); John Moston, 1637, John Mosson, 1673 in   IGI   (Prees, Shrops); William Mosson, 1669, William Moston, 1715 in   IGI   (Saint Giles Cripplegate, London).","3  English:  see  Mossom  ."]},{"name":"Mostin","meanings":["1  English, Welsh:  see  Mostyn  .","2  English:  see  Moston  ."]},{"name":"Mostyn","meanings":["Welsh and English: habitational name from Mostyn in Flintshire, Wales, the name of which is derived from Old English <i>mos</i> ‘bog’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’.","History: This surname was adopted by a 16th-century Lord of Mostyn, Thomas ap Richard ap Hywel, and his brother Piers."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Leuca","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of   Luke  , now also used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Luke","meanings":["Middle English vernacular form of   Lucas  , Latin form of the post-classical Greek name <i>Loukas</i> ‘man from Lucania’. This owes its perennial popularity throughout Christian Europe to the fact that, from the 2nd century onwards, the third gospel in the New Testament has been ascribed to the Lucas or Luke mentioned at various places in Acts and in the Epistles. Little is known about him beyond the facts that he was a doctor, a Gentile, and a friend and convert of St Paul. The name was borne by the character  Luke Skywalker  in the film Star Wars (  1977 ), and rose sharply in popularity in the 1990s."]},{"name":"Luka","meanings":["Anglicized respelling of   Luca ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Leuca Moston was born in 1085, in Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Ranulph de Kingsley in 1105, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died from 1142 to 1182, in Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1085–from 1142 to 1182":"1085–1142 kuni 1182","1080–1135":"1080–1135","1105–1140":"1105–1140","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1136–1244":"1136–1244","1085–1182":"1085–1182","1080":"1080","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1105":"1105","from 1142 to 1182":"1142 kuni 1182","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","about 1105":"umbes 1105","1244":"1244","about 1135":"umbes 1135","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England","Kingsley, Cheshire, England":"Kingsle